I'm glad movies like The Best of Enemies exist. I never knew of a story like this (real talk, schools don't really teach much of anything related to racism due to budget cuts, uncomfortable topic & revisionism). I am glad that I did see it. For a decade, civil rights activist, Ann Atwater (played by Taraji P Henson) & Ku Klux Klan leader C.P. Ellis (Saw Rockwell) agree to co-chair a two-week meeting to vote on the desegregation of schools in Durham, North Carolina. I could give y'all a deeper historical background on the matter, but this is Instagram, not The Smithsonian. In any case, what I enjoyed about this movie, is how it doesn't BS around racism. No overbearing stories from white folks saying "they don't see color" or "one human race". The focus is mostly on the events of that era. Sam Rockwell continues his run of great acting performances playing Ellis. Taraji, I thought, was really good, as well. Bruce McGill is really good playing as Carvie Oldham. His character is one of the more insidious ones in the film. West Bentley is solid. I will say that makeup department didn't do Henson any favors with her costume while playing Atwater. She looked uncomfortable, at times, playing this person. I don't know how the real Ann Atwater walked, but it looked odd in spots. This movie may require you to do some reading on these people. It couldn't hurt. I've seen the mixed reviews, so I guess I understand some of the complaints, but I thoroughly enjoyed this movie. It felt real, impactful & it's genuine.  #TheBestofEnemies #wandererfilmreviews #tarajiphenson #samrockwell 
4.5 out of 5
